'''PÃ¡draig Mac Fhearghusa''' is an [[Irish language]] poet, magazine editor and language activist.
He was born in [[Ballineen]] in West [[County Cork|Cork]] in 1947. He graduated from [[University College Dublin]] in 1970 with a BA in Irish, history and philosophy and obtained a Higher Diploma in Education from [[Trinity College, Dublin]], in 1971. He has worked both as a primary and secondary teacher, and in 1978 helped found a [[Gaelscoil]], Scoil LÃ¡n-Ghaeilge Mhic Easmainn, in [[Tralee]]. He has been active in the promotion of Irish and in 2008 was elected as President of the [[Gaelic League]].<ref>Indymedia-PÃ¡draig Mac Fhearghusa http://www.indymedia.ie/article/84021/</ref><ref>Irish Writers Online-Mac Fhearghusa, PÃ¡draig http://www.irishwriters-online.com/mac-fhearghusa-padraig/</ref> He held this post until 2011, when [[Donnchadh Ã hAodha]] was elected.
He has won recognition as a poet. His collection ''Mearcair'' won the [[Oireachtas na Gaeilge]] National Poetry Prize in 1996, and another collection, ''An Dara BÃ¡s'', won the same prize in 2002.<ref>Irish Writers Online-Mac Fhearghusa, PÃ¡draig http://www.irishwriters-online.com/mac-fhearghusa-padraig/</ref> He has contributed two poems to the Irish Poetry Reading Archive: 'An Teaghlach Naofa agus Naomh Eoin i dTÃ­rdhreach' and 'Eibhlinn'.<ref>Irish Poetry Reading Archive-PÃ¡draig Mac Fhearghusa http://libguides.ucd.ie/ipra/readingsmton</ref>
He is also editor of the Irish language literary monthly [[Feasta]].
